  "rules": {
    "Runtime.0003": {
      "id": "Runtime.0003",
      "description": "Applications running on frameworks older than .NET Framework 4.8 could have potential compatibility issues.\n\nIf you are targeting Managed Instance on Azure App Service, run the app on .NET Framework 4.8 (preinstalled) without retargeting if feasible; review runtime breaking changes and validate on Managed Instance staging.\n\nAzure App Service runs apps on .NET Framework 4.8 or .NET Framework 3.5. Upgrade to a newer target framework or double check that your application works correctly when running on .NET Framework 4.8.\n\nApps that already run on .NET Framework 3.5 or .NET Framework 4.8 do not need changed even if they target an older framework version.\n\nAlthough retargeting to .NET Framework 4.8 will address this issue, it is not necessary. It is only necessary to ensure that the app runs correctly on .NET Framework 3.5 or .NET Framework 4.8. Applications built against older versions of the .NET Framework can run on newer versions (like 4.8) and the runtime will automatically tweak certain behaviors so that the runtime behaves as much as possible as the targeted version. Breaking change documentation mentions both runtime breaking changes and retargeting breaking changes. Runtime breaking changes refer to differences in behavior when applications are run on a newer version of the .NET Framework. These are the behavioral differences which cannot be tweaked away and will matter for applications migrating to Azure App Service. Retargeting breaking changes are changes which only manifest when an app targets a newer version of the .NET Framework. These should not cause issues during App Service migration scenarios because apps do not need re-targeted.\n\nActions to address this issue:\n    1. Review breaking changes between the version of the .NET Framework the application runs on now and .NET Framework 4.8 to make sure none are likely to affect the application.\n    2. Test the application running on .NET Framework 3.5 or .NET Framework 4.8 to ensure it works as expected.",
      "title": "Old .NET Framework dependency detected",
      "severity": "potential",
      "effort": 3,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": ".NET Framework Breaking Changes",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2250029"
        },
        {
          "title": ".NET Framework 4.8 on App Service",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2251730"
        },
        {
          "title": "Configuration builders for ASP.NET",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2251829"
        }
      ],
      "labels": []
    },
    "Runtime.0002": {
      "id": "Runtime.0002",
      "description": "Upgrade to newer target framework to get better cloud experience.\n\nIf you are targeting Managed Instance on Azure App Service, validate on .NET Framework 4.8 or move to .NET 10. Persist any runtime prerequisites via install scripts; test in staging before production.\n\nWhile if targeting other Azure compute services:\n\nApplication targeting .NET framework lower than 4.7.1 might missing features that would be needed for some cloud scenarios like scaling or getting secrets from secure external sources.\n\nAzure App Service runs apps on .NET Framework 4.8 or .NET Framework 3.5. Apps running on on .NET Framework versions older than .NET Framework 4.8 could have potential compatibility issues. It is recommended to test your application running on .NET Framework 4.8. Note that it is not necessary to re-target to .NET Framework 4.8, only to validate that the app correctly runs on that version of .NET Framework.\n\nIn the long term it is also recommended to upgrade your application to latest supported .NET 8\u002B which would significantly increase performance of your application. Use tools like .NET Upgrade Assistant to help with upgrading your application to newer .NET.",
      "title": "Upgrade to newer target framework to get better cloud experience",
      "severity": "optional",
      "effort": 3,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": "[Managed Instance] Install scripts",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2347059"
        },
        {
          "title": ".NET Framework Breaking Changes",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2250029"
        },
        {
          "title": ".NET Framework 4.8 on App Service",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2251730"
        },
        {
          "title": "Upgrade to latest .NET with Upgrade Assistant",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?LinkID=2202641"
        }
      ],
      "labels": []
    },
    "Runtime.0001": {
      "id": "Runtime.0001",
      "description": "Out of support .NET target framework is detected.\n\nIf you are targeting Managed Instance on Azure App Service, target .NET 10 for best cloud experience or validate on .NET 4.8/3.5 (preinstalled). Use .NET Upgrade Assistant and run staging validation on Managed Instance.\n\n.NETCoreApp or .NET 5.0 target frameworks are out of support and Azure App Service sandbox does not have runtime installed for them. It is recommended to upgrade to .NET 8\u002B or deploy your application in a self-contained mode which would allow you to bring framework dependencies with your application.\n\nAlternatively, you could deploy your application to Azure App Service as a container and manage the contents of the container yourself, while keeping other benefits of App Service.\n\nOther alternatives, depending on the architecture of the application, could be to host your app in Azure VM, ACR or Azure Kubernetes service.",
      "title": "Out of support .NET target framework is detected",
      "severity": "mandatory",
      "effort": 3,
      "links": [
        {
          "title": ".NET on Azure App Service",
          "url": "https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2251907"
        },
